segments.text: The chairman of the council was running it.
And he was the head of industrial education.
Right, right.
In fact, as a young professor at A&M, he had Earl Rutter in his class.
Did you know that?
No.
Oh.
And so they were really close friends.
Mm-hmm.
all of the stuff that went on between them.
It was a very collegial affair between them.
And I appreciated Chris Johnman recommending me to Earl Rudder.
But, Rudman had been there since he hired Barry Bryant.
I'm pretty sure he was the councilman.
I understand that his picture was on the front page of Life magazine.
with the old water tower in the background and how the Aggies hire a football coach or something like that.
I've never seen that thing lately.
I think I remember seeing it when it happened, because I was at Baylor in those years.
By the way, after I accepted the contract from, that reminds me, the contract to come to A&M, Baylor
tried to hire me there for exactly the same job at half the money.
That was something.
Baylor has sensed over the days that they've improved their situation really a great deal.
But it was pretty poor pay.
Man, I was really in high cotton to come down here.
Twice what I would have gotten there.
Let's see.
Campus reaction to Mr.
Rudder's death?
Never forget it, the last day of my life, seeing the procession east of the academic building.
Quiet, completely quiet column of people running to file taxes.
The column had been tested in the system building there.
And for me, going then to the memorial service in G. Raleigh, Alan Shivers, LBJ, everybody that mattered, John Connolly, all the great Texans were there.
All right, you stayed with the counseling for how long?
Until 70.
And then what?
And then I became associate dean of education under Frank Hubert.
I still taught some of the courses that I've been always teaching.
But the way that worked out, Dean Hubert had had someone writing the proposal to create a college of education.
He'd already created the College of Science and the College of Business and all those others.
And he was about to create the College of Liberal Arts and the College of Education.
The person who was writing that proposal for him
had said, had left suddenly in the middle of the year.
And he knew that I'd been here nine years and I was sort of looking for a place to go somewhere else and so he called me in and offered me half time off to right finish that proposal and
I've forgotten when he offered to take me on as associate dean, but in that spring semester there very soon after I started doing the work.
So this is happening at about the time of Mr.
Rudder's death and an interim president.
Yeah, yeah.
I got the impression that things were a little bit iffy around the campus while we had the interim president there for a while.
party to the higher administration things.
Even though I was associate dean, I was for students, associate dean for students.
And so I didn't have any much contact with the upper level, mid-level administration.
As far as you know, did Dean Hubert, was he very positive about being dean of education as that big college is broken up?
I always had the impression that that was his aim as soon as he came.
Same, I have that same feeling.
I don't have anything to back it up except for... Well, I think University of Texas' experience with Silver over there might have had something to do with it.
They never did break up the College of Arts and Science over there to this day.
And I thought that was too much for one man to handle.
and maintain equality with the cross.
Describe his style of deaning.
He gave you a job to do and turns you loose and lets you do it.
I had a conference with him every Monday morning and told him what to do.
I came on as associate dean June the 1st.
after this spring.
I'm working with a coordinating board and with him and everybody getting this proposal.
And took it to Austin, came back to Austin again.
All that stuff.
I went on board and he took three weeks vacation.
There was another associate dean, but he made it very clear that I was in charge while he was gone.
So you almost started office.
And it was an interesting time.
All right, so you then went to academic council meetings and dean's meetings, APC meetings.
Yeah.
We had an associate dean's that did more of the work then, but yeah.
All right, who presided over the meeting of the deans during that period?
Well it was only a month.
He was gone three weeks.
So I really didn't go to a meeting of the deans.
I was not called to go to a dean's meeting.
I immediately started going to the associate dean's meeting.
Because I'm thinking Byers was the, Horace Byers was the- I believe Horace Byers was the person that everybody went to at that time.
By the way, he lived in this house at the time.
Really?
Yeah.
Didn't know that.
What do you think were Dean Hubert's goals for the College of Education?
Make it the best teacher preparation college in the state of the nation, if he could.
And what do you think he thought were the key steps to do to achieve that goal?
Well, he had a lot of feeling about the early teaching experience.
As far as I can tell, it was not a good situation.
In fact, I don't think they had a teaching experience in the freshman and sophomore years at the time.
They didn't get exposed to teaching at all at that time.
And he moved in that direction.
He was suspicious of bureaucracy at the same time.
I'll never forget, we had
One of the buzzwords at the time was performance-based teacher education, performance-based teacher counselor training, and all this.
And one of our Monday morning meetings that I had with him alone, he said, and that is, he said, all this performance-based stuff, he said, it's not going to amount to anything.
I thought in my head, most of the time I thought in my head, he said, 10 years from now, it's going to be the same.
They'll forget this whole business.
And I'll never forget the endless hours we worked on that.
And the counseling program, of which I was a part by then, my faculty responsibility was as part of the counselor training program in the Department of Educational Psychology.
We worked countless hours devising a performance-based counselor training program.
And we forgot it in two or three years.

But one of the reasons, one of the things he did which sort of moved me out of the position was we had a consortium of local school superintendents and college faculty and a third entity, oh, the educational service centers, a consortium to work on teacher training.
And since I hadn't come out of
teacher trained.
I had been a psychologist all the way through.
He thought that you could do better by moving Limbacher into that position.
And me go back to the old blackberry college to teach him full time.
And he gave me five thousand dollars.
He only had a project he wanted to do.
Move Limbacher in and said you take this and I want you to do a field survey
recent graduates of teacher training here and see what they think the weakest point in their training was.

I spent the spring semester, before I really got down to teaching again, I spent the spring semester, this was my event in 73, two or three years later, going around the countryside talking to school superintendents and principals about people they'd hired in the 12th century, talking to the people who said,
Give him a short report after that, it was true.
Do you remember the high points of that report?
The high point was that there was not enough about teaching, enough about classroom management.
And what was the strength?
That was a weakness, what was the strength?
Well, the strength was they came A&M.
They were, A&M graduates were premium hires, especially in health and physical education.
People would, superintendents from all over the countryside would flock to get those people because I- Why?
Because they had a rigid academic program, even those days.
There were not a bunch of football players.
Who deserved the credit for that?
Well, you're going to have to give Carl Linus part of it, at least.
And that started before Frank Hubert and I ever came.
Carl Linus was doing a good job of preparing PE teachers a long time ago.
Any other names in that department appropriate to mention?
In health and PE?
Well, of course, very soon, believe it or not, he was upgrading.
And he brought in, that's when he brought in George Jessup from California.
Jessup.
J-E-S-S-U-P. George Jessup.
His specialty of course was human performance.
Not the kind of performance based on the stuff we were talking about before, but I mean physical human performance.
And he started a lab over there which is going today.
George is not a part of it.
He started that thing.
And I was one of his guinea pigs.
The first one he called over and gave that battery test where he spent two hours running me through the mills like the astronauts.
I think they're still going today.
Yeah.
Other key family members in?
In health and P.E.
Mm-hmm.
Oh, there are a good bunch of people.
I hesitate to single out any of them that I became friends with.
I became friends with a whole bunch of people.
Now, let's see.
Grunemann in industrial ed, that was over,
Was that in engineering?
Engineering, but they didn't have too much connection with engineering.
They were really an education department.
Ag education was a part of agriculture.
In fact, when I drew up the chart to take to the coordinating board, you had a line going through the Dean of Agriculture and one going through the Dean of Education.
But all the other departments were solely in the College of Education.
I see.
So there was...
What were the other departments in?
Curriculum instruction, administration, educational psychology, ag education, industrial education.
Education and physical health, H and PE.
Yeah.
Did campus reputation, was one of those thought to be harder than the others academically or softer than the others academically?
Yeah, there's no doubt that health and physical education had the reputation to be the toughest.
The toughest?
Yeah.
All right, did any of them have the reputation of being the softest?
I don't know of any, but I was just wondering if.
If any, it would be curriculum and instruction.
There were, you looked to see where the football players were.
And some of them went to industrial education.
And some of them came to curriculum instruction.
But see, education and psychology didn't have any undergraduates, so we didn't suffer that way.
But when I was associate dean, at that time we had a policy that we just do darn near anything in terms of transferring students.
It's become a nightmare now to transfer from engineering to education or business or whatever.
But in those days, if a guy came in and could convince me that he was misplaced in engineering, back to my counseling days, I remembered very well.
So many people were caught up in the romance of the space age and the romance of engineering that they went over there whether they ought to go over there or not.
So I was pulling people into education and doing everything I could legally, which was quite a bit.
to get them at the College of Education and get them graduated.
And at that time I was allowed to take F's off their degree plan.
Still had them on the transcript.
I made out a degree plan for them and I didn't put down the F's and the D's.
I put down the courses they made up.
And then they had to continue to make good courses in education, and they graduated.
And it's much harder to do that today.
It's not impossible, but it's much, much harder today.

The reason I know this, of course, is because my daughter, Chris Boyd, is in the same position this day and time, where I hear her tell about how hard it is to transfer from college education, to transfer from general studies, which she supervises.
But for the two and a half years I was there, I had pretty much free hand.
But we didn't have any identity.
Dean Hubert and I decided we'd have a complication of all education majors.
We put out plenty of publicity and we got a big meeting room, 330 seats over the temperature building.
and specified a night we thought that it would be available to anybody but a handful.
Which gave us a signal that there was no real identity with the college there.
And I'm not sure we have any identity anywhere else the same way on the campus.
You have some identity with departments.
There they have an in-group feeling.
But he was looking for the in-group feeling there.
And I guess one of the reasons he hired me was, hey, here's a counselor.
Maybe he can help us with this business of creating an atmosphere.
In the early 70s, when the College of Education was created, Dean's office was in...
The old library.
The library.
Then moved over to academic... Oh, uh...
Let's see what that sequence was.
Don't I remember his office, Hubert's office, being on the south end of academic?
Yeah, first floor.
Yeah.
That's where the reason for that was the Department of Education had been there.
Okay.
See?
And when he became dean, for a while he was also department head of curriculum instruction as well as dean.
Where were the other academicians?
other departments of education.
The old red brick building that they called, oh it used to have Textile Engineering in it.
It sits over there now.
Where?
I forget.
It's north of the library, somewhere in there.
It's now been torn down.
Yeah, and then our department scattered out.
Part of them went to one building and part to another until we finished the education building.
When the college is created, did it have master's degrees?
And doctor's degrees.
And doctoral degrees, both at that point?
Yes.
The way he did that was check a little block.
You haven't heard that tale?
No, no.
share that.

When he applied, I didn't see this piece of paper, but when he applied to the Coordinating Board for what degrees will you offer at the College of Education, it had little boxes there to check, bachelor's, master's, doctor's.
So we checked them all.
That's all the rest of it.
Didn't have to go through a study or anything.
We started out in 68 or whenever it was, we had that.
And we had a PhD right then.
I was chairman of the, I guess the second Ph.D. in Canada.
I was chairman of the committee, Wesley Saunders.
We had, the first one was an education major, but as an Arab from Egypt, and he went back to Egypt I guess, but Wesley was the first one after him.
Well, I say I was the chair.
I was the working chair at Haskell.
Somebody else was the chair.
I forget who now, but because it was in test and measurement, they let me run the thing.
And Wesley and I grounded out pretty quick there.
But yeah, that's where we got the PhD.
And when we went, that was as the Department of Education and Psychology.
Then we went to the College of Education,
all the five departments, six departments, had the same degrees offered.
See, that's the upper level.
So at Sac, they never did have to go through a coordinating board, you know, a stealth study in order to get their Ph.D.
So it was an Ed.D.
and a Ph.D. either or both.
Either or both.
Okay.
In every department.
In every department.
Yeah.
Imagine what it would be like today to try to get a number of southern associations and Texas Education Agency staff studies out down 30 years.
Wow.
Do you remember in those changes any examples of higher administration and or board of directors, it would have been called then, involvement, positive or negative?
Nope, I don't.
There may have been some.
I don't know.
I think Dean Hubert's influence statewide was really considerable.
And I'm reading between the lines here.
I think he had a little bit of an end with the Texas Education Agency as well as the Board of Education.
I think you're right.
First of all, he'd worked for Dr. Edgar.
Yeah.
and I have always assumed that that was the connection that may have led Earl Rudder to know who Frank Hubert was in the summer of 1959.
Well, I think you have to check this out, but I thought that the Rudders and the Huberts lived
neighborhood close in Austin.
Oh, didn't know that.
Across the alley or whatever.
Didn't know that.
You have to check that out to be sure.
Because they were there at the same time.
At the same time, yeah.
He stayed over there.
Rudder came to the Texas Edge, came to the Rudder Land Board in 52, I believe, when we had a big scandal over there.
I was in graduate school in Texas, so I knew all about it.
In fact, the guy who was
Baskin-Giles.
Baskin-Giles.
His sister was in my classes at the University of Texas.
Sort of a situation there.
But then he, Rudder, came over and stayed about six or eight years.
And came over here as Vice President.
And he brought some people with him.
He brought, I think he brought Frank Hewlett.
I think he brought the guy who became the Comptroller.
He lived across the street from me down .
And his wife is still in First Presbyterian Church down there with him.
Oh, oh, oh.
Do you know who that is?
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Oh, cool.
Well, I think Rudder brought him.
OK.
Fill me in chronologically as you recall it.
Mr.
Rudder dies.
And for most of us, it seemed comparatively sudden.
Yeah.
Do you remember any feelings of the interim period?
I can remember uncertainty.
And they didn't trust the guy who was the guy who was interim.
The general was at Freeman.
I think it was Clyde Freeman.
Clyde Freeman.
I think so.
People felt he didn't know anything about the academic division.
They were afraid of him.
those months there went by while he acted.
I know the guy and I didn't have much feeling one way or the other, but I felt the campus was a little uncertain of itself.
Do you remember any reaction to hearing that they had selected a new president?
That fall?
No, except relief.
You know the story about Tiger Teague being on the campus and
when Williams came, don't you?
No, share that.
Down there, and of course we're in the time of students marching on the president's homes, and so the students marched on the president's home.
And Tiger Thief went to the door and said, oh my God, they've got to march on the president's home.
They're down here to protest.
Williams walked on out.
They'd come to welcome me, not to criticize me.
That was one of the unusual things.
The whole cadet corps was out there, I think, and others were out there in the front yard to greet the new president.
What was your impression of Jack Williams?
Man, we could never have, we could look for years and never got a better one.
He complemented completely and totally Rudder's regime.
Complemented it.
And he told a joke the first time he spoke in front of the faculty.
He told a joke, I'm sure you were there, about the old Aggie who talked to him and said, Mr. Williams, you're the first non-Aggie.
We're going to be watching you damn close.
And what was your impression of his various abilities?
Man, there's just no question.
I thought he was ideal in every way.
It's too bad he couldn't have lived longer and made an oral remark.
Of course that summer, Frank Hubert had sent me off, I was just in, and he'd sent me off to this seminar for new administrators.
Remember that thing?
Did you ever go to that thing?
You want to hear?
Yeah.
I've spoken to it 21 years ago.
Yeah, okay, but
Did you go through it as a participant?
We had a week here and a week up on the TCU campus.
And Williams, of course, addressed us there.
And I never forget the joke he told about the steam whistle.
You heard that one?
You ought to get that one down if you haven't heard it.
First morning he came to work and the whistle blew at the power plant.
And at 12 o'clock it blew again.
He asked the secretary, what was that?
He said, that's 8, 12, 1, and 5.
That's the whistle it was.
And he said, I picked up the phone and called the plant.
Told them, never blow that thing again.
This is an academic institution.
And to this group of budding administrators, he says, and that
It's more initiative than I would have taken at any other time in my administrative career.
Not daring to do that.
My first day on the job, stop the whistle.
Who were his key associates?
That's harder for me to get at.
Nah.
I believe you're going to have to get a lot of that from somewhere else, because I don't remember.
By this time, I was out of the administrative cycle and into being a new faculty member full time in a department which had a few troubles.
All right, let's look at these two presidents now.
I'm going to ask the negative.
What were the key decisions that you can think of during their
times.
Well one minor one that so fits the other thing about Williams was we were having all the bomb threats around the campus and Williams called the associate deans together and said
You're the administrators and so forth.
We said, I'm here to tell you that we're going to run this campus.
We're going to take all precautions.
We're not going to close down any building any time for a bomb threat.
That's an early decision, and I thought it was the kind of decision which needed to be made, and he made it.
How many more bomb threats did we have?
I don't think so.
Whether we got out or not.
That's the one I remember now.
There must have been some others.
He also had the...
He is the one who... Let's see.
What about his...
described Williams as a speaker before.
Complete control.
Every word as if he'd planned it weeks in advance and spoken just exactly with the right inflection of his voice.
That was my impression of it.
Yeah.
And let's see.
In education, y'all didn't make any major changes under Williams because y'all were already there in terms of the degrees and the organization and so forth.
We did get national recognition for our programs from the professional societies.
Educational psychology did at the time.
We had counseling in psychology and school psychology.
besides being accredited, you also get approval by the National Associations, and we got that through long before the Department of Psychology did, by the way.
Long before.
Do you remember any comments relating to those reviews?
Any judgments?
We didn't get ever, there was never a question.
as we went forward.
We presented enough data.
We got so much support from the Institute of Statistics, from the Department of Psychology, from the Department of Sociology.
There was never a question that we would get it the first time we went forward with the proposal.
And it was renewed.
I was coordinator of the counseling program at the time.
And no question about it.
At that time, with whom did the A&M College of Education most often compare itself in the region?
Who was the competing program, the parallel program?
Well, always a little bit of comparison between the equal sized University of Texas and us there.
But the other teacher prep institutions
Commerce had a real good reputation.
Huntsville had a good reputation.
